"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-08-03-olympics-schedule-results-athletics-gymnastics-rowing-21351281\", \"text\": \"Day eight of theParis2024Olympicshas begun withTeam GBhoping to add to their medal haul after a fantastic opening week.  Rather fittingly,seven medals were won on day sevenof the games including three golds in the rowing, trampolining and equestrian, marking Great Britain's best ever start to an Olympics.  There are a whopping 31 gold medals on offer today, perhaps the biggest being the women's 100m which Dina Asher-Smith will be hoping to win.  Over in the gymnastics arena, Max Whitlock went for a third consecutive gold on the pommel horse and but was denied a fairytale ending to his Olympics journey, finishing fourth.  Team GB have won six medals so far today, including gold in the men's eight, capping off a superb games in the rowing.  This blog is now closed. For the latest updates, visitMetro's Sport page.  Thanks for joining us today and be sure to join us tomorrow when Team GB will go for gold in the swimming pool and on the golf course.  Oh and there is the small matter of Novak Djokovic vs Carlos Alcaraz\\u2026  So that's day eight done and dusted with six more medals for Team GB, which leaves them fifth in the table behind China, the USA, France and Australia.  One gold in the men's eight rowing and five bronzes in the rowing, windsurfing, equestrian, gymnastics and athletics.  One of the huge stories at the start of the Paris games centred around the Canadian women's football team after it was revealed that they had been using drones to spy on rivals for years.  Their head coach was sent home and they were docked six points but managed to qualify from the group stage.  But their eventful journey at the Olympics has now come to end after they lost to Germany on penalties in the quarter-finals.  Double disappointment for Britain's swimmers after they finish seventh in the final of the mixed 4x100m medley relay - and lose their world record.  The USA claim gold with a blistering time of 3 minutes and 37.43 seconds.  Kathleen Dawson, James Wilby, Duncan Scott and Anna Hopkin did not look at the races tonight but they will hopefully bounce back in the upcoming relays.  The boxing ring has been a fairly miserable place for Team GB these games but thankfully Lewis Richardson has salvaged something.  He beat Jordanian Zeyad Eashash tonight to reach the semi-finals of the men's 71kg event and as there are no bronze medal bouts in boxing, he is guaranteed to win a medal of some description.  Samuel Reardon, Laviai Nielsen, Alex Haydock-Wilson and Amber Anning ran a British record time in order to get bronze in the 4x400m mixed relay.  But they will also be joined on the podium by Nicole Yeargin who ran for Team GB in the heats to help qualify them for the final.  Daryll Neita wasn't expected to win a medal but she came so, so, so close.  The Brit finishes the women's 100m final in fourth place - just 0.04 seconds off the podium.  The gold goes to Julien Alfred\\u00a0- St Lucia's first ever Olympic medal.  The first athletics medal of the games for Team GB comes courtesy of the 4x400m mixed relay team.  Congrats to Samuel Reardon, Laviai Nielsen, Alex Haydock-Wilson and Amber Anning.  But the star of that race was the Netherlands who surged forward from fourth on the last lap to pip the USA to gold on the line.  One of Team GB's medal winners today was Emma Wilson who claimed bronze in the women's windsurfing.  But having dominated the event until the final, she was distraught not to have won the gold and afterward slammed the competition's format.  'I had a 60-point lead at the World Championships, a 30-point lead here. It's obvious I had a disadvantage with this scoring system.'  Imani Lansiquot is the second Brit to fall at the semi-final phase of the women's 100m.  Third time lucky for Daryll Neita?  Yes! The 27-year-old finishes second in her race with a time of 10.97 seconds. She will sprint for gold in just over an hour's time.  Jamaica's Shelly-Ann Fraser-Pryce has pulled out of theOlympics100m semi final on Saturday night.  Not a good start to the night for Team GB.  A relatively sluggish performance from Dina Asher-Smith sees her finish fifth in her semi-final meaning she will not progress to tonight's 100m final.  Imane Khelif declared, 'I am a woman', after securing her first-everOlympicboxing medal.  Team GB's Tommy Fleetwood has finished his third round on the golf course, carding at two-under-par for the day and 11-under overall.  As it stands that puts him in the bronze medal position - just one shot behind Spain's Jon Rahm and USA's Xander Schauffele.  Tomorrow's final round is set to be epic\\u2026  Max Whitlock is a 'gymnast no longer' and struggled to hold back the tears as he reflected on his incredible career in an interview with BBC Sport:  'It is very raw at the moment and I would have loved for it to end in a better way here in Paris. But I do not want anyone to look at the way I am feeling now and think that it is a reflection of my career, I am so proud standing here today.  'It was a challenge getting here. I could have quit after Tokyo and I decided to come back. I think giving yourself a good shot, giving yourself the opportunity to go forward rather than quitting out of fear of failure.  'I am proud to be here. Of course I would have wanted for it to end better but my decision to come here was not based on the outcome. It was based on just being here at my fourth Olympics and to have that fourth Olympics in my journey.  'It is gutting and disappointing, of course it is, but I am proud. I am done now, I am not a gymnast any longer. I have done my final routine and I can be very happy.'  Imane Khelif\\u00a0was in tears after she guaranteed herself an Olympic medal with a dominant victory over Hungary's Anna Luca Hamori.  The Algerian, whose participation inParishas been met with controversy, impressed in her quarter-final, convincingly winning all three rounds.  She was overcome with emotion in the ring afterward, with the win meaning she is now guaranteed at least a bronze medal in the women's 66kg division. Read more here:  It's not to be for Max Whitlock. He finishes fourth with a score of 15.200.  Nevertheless, he bows out a British sporting great, with six Olympic medals to his name including three gold.  Ireland's Rhys McClenaghan wins the gold after a stunning routine scores him 15.533.  Max Whitlock is the second to go in the men's pommel horse final.  His last ever act at the Olympics before retirement is good but not enough to take the lead. 15.200 puts him in the silver medal spot.  Six athletes still to perform. A nervous wait begins\\u2026  With just 3.4km to go in the road race, Remco Evenepoel was certain to win, only to dramatically pick up a puncture.  The Belgian managed to get on a spare bike however and held onto his commanding lead to claim the gold medal.  SOUND ON! \\u00f0\\u009f\\u0094\\u008aBelgian leader Remco Evenepoel has a puncture inside the final four kilometres of the men's road race \\u00f0\\u009f\\u0098\\u00b2#BBCOlympics#Olympics#Paris2024pic.twitter.com/fxJJLKkDCP  Four golds in Rio. Now three (and counting) in Paris. Take a bow Simone Biles!  The American's victory on the vault was never in doubt and she can still add to her medal collection in the beam and floor finals on Monday.  ArrowMORE:'You all are so f***ing miserable' - Simone Biles defends husband after he wears her gold medal  ArrowMORE:Shelly-Ann Fraser-Pryce out of Olympics 100m final after injury and late rule change  ArrowMORE:Fans clash at Olympics as man rips Taiwan banner out of woman's hands  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy\"}"